## Priority 3: Technical Confirmation

### Web Audio Sample-Lock (Q5)
**CONFIRMED.** Multiple `AudioBufferSourceNode.start(t)` calls with the same `t = audioCtx.currentTime` from within the same JavaScript frame are processed in the same audio rendering block (~128 samples / ~2.9ms at 44.1kHz). The audio graph processes in discrete 128-sample blocks; any `.start()` calls scheduled for the same block boundary fire simultaneously to sub-sample precision.

**Caveat:** `audioCtx.currentTime` is quantized — it advances in ~2.9ms steps, always reporting the start of the NEXT block. All `.start()` calls in the same JS frame see the same `currentTime` value and schedule to the same block. Practical effect: guaranteed sample-locked across Chrome, Safari, Firefox on modern hardware. No per-browser caveats beyond the block-quantization behavior (same on all engines).

### Lookahead Scheduler Reference (Q6)
**Chris Wilson's "A Tale of Two Clocks"** — https://web.dev/articles/audio-scheduling — is the canonical reference. Parameters: **25ms setTimeout interval, 100ms lookahead window**. Pattern: each tick schedules any events within the next 100ms into the audio graph using `audioCtx.currentTime`-based absolute timestamps; `setTimeout` only drives the check loop, never the actual audio timing.

IRCAM WebAudio Tutorials (https://ircam-ismm.github.io/webaudio-tutorials/scheduling/timing-and-scheduling.html) is an updated reference with the same pattern (period 50ms / lookahead 100ms variant) and explicitly cites Wilson's article. No npm package needed — ~50 lines of vanilla JS per the Wilson article; demo-builder should implement `Scheduler.js` following this pattern directly.

